    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p><persName ref="pe0006">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Bailey</persName> sent me a
                    proof on just the same paper: but I hope next month all will be finished<note type="editorial">Pennant is referring to the completion of <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0209"><hi rend="italic">A Map of
                                    Scotland, the Hebrides and Part of England adapted to Mr
                                    Pennant's Tours</hi></title></bibl>, published in 1777.</note>
                    Be so good as to inclose (the first week in April) To <persName ref="pe0015">Sir
                        Roger M.</persName>
                    <placeName ref="pl0734">Bruton street</placeName>
                    <placeName ref="pl0699">London</placeName>.</p>
                <p>P.1. of my <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0142">Sir D<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lindsay</title></bibl> is the Prologue. The last is 140 <hi rend="underline">Let there be made</hi> &amp;c In short the same as y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> but I cannot find the lines I quote which I found
                    quoted in another book.<note type="editorial">Pennant is attempting to locate
                        the source of the poem on the death of Cardinal David Beaton quoted in his
                            <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0010"><hi rend="italic">Tour in
                                    Scotland and Voyage to the Hebrides 1772 Part II</hi></title>
                            (London: 1776),<biblScope unit="page"> p.194</biblScope></bibl>. See his
                        letter to Paton on 14 February 1777.</note></p>
                <p>Be so good as forward the inclosed.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am <lb/>Dear Sir <lb/>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi></salute><signed><persName ref="pe0232"> T.
                        Pennant</persName></signed>

                <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> March. 7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                    <lb/>1777.</dateline></closer>

                <postscript>
                    <p>I wish much for any corrections or remarks on my <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0010">last tour</title></bibl> I hope you will now
                        encrease my debt of 17<hi rend="superscript"><hi rend="underline">Shillings</hi></hi> that I may send you a bill. the other was too
                        trifling.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p><address>
                        <addrLine>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Paton</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Custom house</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Edinburgh</addrLine>
                    </address></p>
            </div>
